Video Landscape - ATUS, Nielsen & Hakuhodo

NBCU Digital Measurement - Blandon C

January 16, 2018

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

As traditional TV viewing declines, the natural question to ask is…where are viewers going? What are they doing? Unfortunately, this very simple question has many answers depending on who you ask. Of critical concern to TV programmers is whether or not there’s a still opportunity to capture viewers attention. The dilemna is presented in this way…“even if we perfectly execute video content, if there’s no opportunity…then what difference does it make”.

The data and information we’ve explored in this analysis, seems to infer that live TV video usage is transferring to video consumption on other platforms, as opposed to other non-video forms of online activity. The data further establishes that more time allocated to online usage does not detract from cross-platform video consumption.

Our analysis utlizes secondary research from U.S Bureau of Labor Statistics’s American Time Usage Survey, Nielsen/Pivotal Research custom research and for comparative analysis a Tokyo based survey conducted by the Hakuhodo research firm.

DATA SOURCES: ATUS, Nielsen & Hakuhodo

The American Time Usage Survey (ATUS) is a very high-level report, that doesn’t distinguish between video viewing platforms. ATUS’s TV usage survey question is covers what is essentially viewing long-form content on any platform. We’ve covered this question look weekday and all days of week viewing. The same principle applies to the computer usage question, it applies to all devices but it excludes gaming. ATUS survey data is gives us a trended look from 2003-2016. There are three charts in our analysis from this data source.

Nielsen and Pivotal research have created custom average audience delivery for cross-platform TV viewing, along with traditional live ratings as well. The date range for this study is from 2008-2016. There are two charts in our analysis from this data set.

Finally, for the purposes of a comparative analysis, we’ll look at survey data from the Hakuhodo research firm. Hakuhodo’s survey also asks about TV viewing, but it is confined to live TV.

DATA EXPLORATION & ANALYSIS

Series ID: TUU10101AA01006114
Series Title: Avg hrs per day - Computer use for leisure, excluding games
Type of estimate: Average hours per day
Activity: Computer use for leisure Day of week: All days
Age: 15 years and over

According to the ATUS survey, respondents report using a computer in any capacity, besides gaming, for .17 hours per day. Although there is a peak starting in 2011, that seems to decline starting in 2015, making the overall trend flat. BLS confirmed that this usage includes mobile usage of social media. The regression shows zero growth per year, and is statisically significant at 99% confidence interval. See output below:

Series ID: TUU10101AA01014236
Series Title: Avg hrs per day - Watching TV
Type of estimate: Average hours per day
Activity: Watching TV
Day of week: All days
Age: 15 years and over

According to the ATUS survey, respondents report watching TV on any platform, all days of the week, for 2.72 hours per day. The regression shows that viewing on any platform has been growing at 1 minute per year from 2003-2016 on average,and is statisically significant at 99% confidence interval. See output below:

CORRELATION ANALYSIS

Essentially there are different sources, with differen methodologies, that indicate Live TV viewing is decreasing while cross-platform TV is increasing. Let’s examine the correlation between these different data sources for further confirmations of their trends.

## ATUS TV & Nielsen Xplatform Correlation       -0.2376375
